  "local_port": 50624,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I share session when login between Laravel and Ruby?",
  "response": "Sharing sessions between Laravel (PHP) and Ruby can be achieved through several approaches. Here are a few methods:\n\n1. Shared Session Storage (Redis)\n\n```php\n// Laravel (config/session.php)\n'driver' => 'redis',\n\n// Ruby (config/initializers/session_store.rb)\nRails.application.config.session_store :redis_store, \n  servers: 'redis://localhost:6379/0',\n  expire_after: 1.day\n```\n\n2. Encrypt/Decrypt Shared Session Cookie\n\n```php\n// Laravel (Sharing session cookie)\npublic function generateSharedSessionCookie($userData)\n{\n    // Encrypt user data\n    $encryptedData = Crypt::encrypt([\n        'user_id' => $userData->id,\n        'email' => $userData->email\n    ]);\n\n    // Create a cookie that can be read by both apps\n    return Cookie::make('shared_session', $encryptedData, 60, null, '.yourdomain.com');\n}\n\n// Ruby (Reading shared session)\nclass SessionController < ApplicationController\n  def validate_shared_session\n    encrypted_cookie = cookies['shared_session']\n    \n    begin\n      # Decrypt using the same key and method as Laravel\n      decrypted_data = decrypt_with_laravel_method(encrypted_cookie)\n      \n      # Validate and create session\n      user = User.find(decrypted_data['user_id'])\n      session[:user_id] = user.id\n    rescue => e\n      # Handle decryption errors\n    end\n  end\nend\n```\n\n3. JWT (JSON Web Tokens) Approach\n\n```php\n// Laravel - Generate JWT\nuse Tymon\\JWTAuth\\Facades\\JWTAuth;\n\npublic function login(Request $request)\n{\n    $credentials = $request->only('email', 'password');\n    \n    if ($token = JWTAuth::attempt($credentials)) {\n        return response()->json([\n            'token' => $token,\n            'user' => auth()->user()\n        ]);\n    }\n}\n\n// Ruby - Validate JWT\nrequire 'jwt'\n\nclass SessionController < ApplicationController\n  def validate_token\n    token = request.headers['Authorization']&.split(' ')&.last\n    \n    begin\n      # Decode JWT using the same secret key\n      decoded_token = JWT.decode(token, Rails.application.secrets.secret_key_base, true, algorithm: 'HS256')\n      \n      # Extract user information\n      user_id = decoded_token[0]['user_id']\n      user = User.find(user_id)\n      \n      # Create session or authenticate\n      session[:user_id] = user.id\n    rescue JWT::DecodeError\n      # Handle invalid token\n    end\n  end\nend\n```\n\n4. Single Sign-On (SSO) Approach\n\n```php\n// Laravel - Authentication Service\npublic function generateSSOToken($userId)\n{\n    $token = Str::random(60);\n    \n    // Store token in cache with user ID\n    Cache::put('sso_token:' . $token, $userId, 300);\n    \n    return $token;\n}\n\n// Ruby - SSO Validation\nclass SsoController < ApplicationController\n  def validate_sso\n    sso_token = params[:token]\n    \n    # Check token in shared cache\n    user_id = Rails.cache.read(\"sso_token:#{sso_token}\")\n    \n    if user_id\n      # Authenticate user\n      user = User.find(user_id)\n      session[:user_id] = user.id\n      \n      # Invalidate token\n      Rails.cache.delete(\"sso_token:#{sso_token}\")\n    else\n      # Invalid or expired token\n    end\n  end\nend\n```\n\n5. Shared Database Session Storage\n\n```php\n// Database Configuration\n// Use a shared database for session storage\n// Configure both Laravel and Ruby to use the same database connection\n\n// Laravel (config/session.php)\n'driver' => 'database',\n'connection' => 'shared_sessions',\n\n// Ruby (config/database.yml)\nshared_sessions:\n  adapter: mysql2\n  host: same_host\n  database: shared_sessions_db\n```\n\nRecommendations:\n1. Use consistent encryption methods\n2. Implement secure token generation\n3. Use HTTPS for all communications\n4. Implement proper error handling\n5. Set appropriate token/cookie expiration\n\nConsiderations:\n- Performance impact\n- Security implications\n- Complexity of implementation\n- Shared infrastructure requirements\n\nChoose the method that best fits your specific architecture and security requirements.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
